---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHero from '../components/PageHero.astro';
import Divider from '../components/Divider.astro';
import { CHALISA_PDF } from '../site.ts';

const qualities = [
  { en: 'Devotion', hi: 'भक्ति', d: 'His heart holds only one name. Hanuman is the very picture of bhakti — love so complete it forgets itself.' },
  { en: 'Strength', hi: 'बल', d: 'He lifted a mountain and leapt across the ocean. Yet his strength bows always in service, never in pride.' },
  { en: 'Service', hi: 'सेवा', d: 'He asks for no reward but the chance to serve Ram. To work for others is, for him, the highest joy.' },
  { en: 'Humility', hi: 'विनम्रता', d: 'The mightiest of beings makes himself the smallest. In humility he finds his greatest power.' },
];

// Hanuman near Nashik
const anjaneri = {
  note: 'The hill where Anjani gave birth to Hanuman rises just outside Nashik, on the road to Trimbakeshwar. Near the summit stand a temple to Anjani Mata — said to be the only one of its kind — and a Hanuman temple, reached by a beautiful trek past ancient caves and Sita’s cave.',
  address: 'Anjaneri, Nashik–Trimbakeshwar Rd, Maharashtra 422213',
  reach: 'About 20 km from Nashik. Drive, or take a Trimbak-bound bus to Anjaneri Phata; Anjaneri village is a ~15-min walk, then it’s a ~1½-hour trek to the temples. Loveliest just after the monsoon.',
  maps: 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Anjaneri+Hill+Hanuman+birthplace+Nashik',
};
const localTemples = [
  { name: 'Takli Gomaya Maruti Mandir', area: 'Takli, Nashik', note: 'Established by Sant Samarth Ramdas in 1633; the Hanuman murti here is shaped from gomaya (cow dung).', maps: 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Takli+Gomaya+Maruti+Mandir+Nashik' },
  { name: 'Dutondya Maruti Mandir', area: 'Panchavati, on the Godavari', note: 'A single stone with Hanuman carved on both faces — do-tondya, “two-faced” — beside the holy river.', maps: 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Dutondya+Maruti+Mandir+Panchavati+Nashik' },
  { name: 'Dakshinmukhi Hanuman Mandir', area: 'Parijat Nagar, Nashik 422005', note: 'A south-facing (dakshinmukhi) Hanuman, dear to devotees in the city.', maps: 'https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Dakshinmukhi+Hanuman+Mandir+Parijat+Nagar+Nashik' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Hanuman-ji"
  description="Hanuman — the perfect devotee of Ram, and the heart of Neem Karoli Baba's path. His qualities, his place in the Ramayana, and the Hanuman Chalisa."
>
  <PageHero
    eyebrow="The perfect devotee"
    deva="श्री हनुमान"
    title="Hanuman-ji"
    lede="Maharaj-ji's whole life flowed from his love of Hanuman — strong and humble, the one whose only wish is to serve Ram. To draw near Maharaj-ji is to be turned toward Hanuman."
  />

  <figure class="h-hero-img reveal" data-zoom>
    <div class="photo">
      <img src="/images/hanuman/ram-naam.jpg" alt="Hanuman seated in devotion, hands folded, haloed by the written name of Ram" width="720" height="1230" fetchpriority="high" />
    </div>
    <figcaption>Hanuman in prayer, haloed by the very name of Ram — <span class="deva">राम नाम</span>.<br /><span class="h-credit">Devotional painting · shared in seva</span></figcaption>
  </figure>

  <article class="shell-narrow prose-deva h-body reveal">
    <p class="h-lead">
      Hanuman is the great devotee — son of Vayu, the wind, and an emanation of Shiva himself.
      In him, every quality a seeker hopes to grow is already perfected: boundless strength laid
      humbly at the feet of God, and a love so single-pointed that it becomes its own kind of power.
    </p>

    <h2>In the Ramayana</h2>
    <p>
      When Sita was carried away to Lanka, it was Hanuman who leapt across the ocean to find her,
      who carried Ram’s ring as a token of hope, and who later bore the whole mountain of healing
      herbs when he could not tell which single plant was needed. Again and again he does the
      impossible — not for himself, but because his Lord has need of it. This is why devotees turn
      to him: <em>“Grant me strength, intelligence and wisdom, and remove my sorrows and
      shortcomings.”</em>
    </p>

    <figure class="h-darbar" data-zoom>
      <div class="photo">
        <img src="/images/hanuman/ram-darbar.jpg" alt="The Ram Darbar — Rama, Sita, Lakshmana and brothers, with Hanuman kneeling in devotion" width="900" height="1230" loading="lazy" />
      </div>
      <figcaption>The Ram Darbar — and there, kneeling at their feet, Hanuman. <span class="h-credit">Raja Ravi Varma · public domain</span></figcaption>
    </figure>

    <Divider class="h-rule" />

    <h2>Why Maharaj-ji pointed to Hanuman</h2>
    <p>
      Neem Karoli Baba built Hanuman temples across India and would not allow devotees to touch
      his own feet — <em>touch Hanuman’s feet instead</em>, he would say. He did not want to be
      the destination; he wanted to be a finger pointing at the moon. Wherever his dhams stand,
      from Kainchi to Taos, a murti of Hanuman stands at their heart. To love Hanuman, Maharaj-ji
      taught, is to learn the only thing worth learning: how to love and serve completely.
    </p>

    <h2>Sankat Mochan — remover of troubles</h2>
    <p>
      Across India, Hanuman is beloved as <em>Sankat Mochan</em> — the one who lifts away
      difficulty and fear. <strong>Tuesday</strong> and Saturday are his days; on them, in homes
      and temples everywhere, devotees light a lamp and sing his praises, and feel their worries
      grow a little smaller. It is said that wherever his name is sung with love, Hanuman himself
      is quietly present, listening.
    </p>

    <h2>Why we sing the Chalisa</h2>
    <p>
      The forty verses of the <strong>Hanuman Chalisa</strong>, composed by the poet-saint
      Tulsidas, are the heartbeat of our Tuesday gathering. You need not follow every word — the
      names do their own work. To sing them together is to borrow a little of Hanuman's courage,
      and a little of his devotion. You can <a href="/satsang/">join us on a Tuesday</a>, or take
      the Chalisa home from the card below.
    </p>
  </article>

  <!-- the four qualities -->
  <section class="shell h-qualities reveal">
    <span class="eyebrow flanked">What he embodies</span>
    <div class="hq-grid">
      {qualities.map((q) => (
        <div class="hq-card card">
          <span class="hq-hi deva">{q.hi}</span>
          <h3>{q.en}</h3>
          <p>{q.d}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- forms of Hanuman -->
  <section class="h-forms reveal">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="h-forms-head">
        <span class="eyebrow flanked">Many forms, one love</span>
        <h2>The forms of Hanuman</h2>
        <p>Across India he is painted a thousand ways — dancing, fierce, five-faced, or simply lost in prayer. Each form is a window onto the same boundless devotion.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="h-forms-grid">
        <figure class="tile" data-zoom><img src="/images/hanuman/dancing.jpg" alt="Golden Tanjore-style painting of Hanuman dancing" loading="lazy" /></figure>
        <figure class="tile" data-zoom><img src="/images/hanuman/panchamukhi.jpg" alt="Panchamukhi Hanuman, the five-faced form" loading="lazy" /></figure>
        <figure class="tile" data-zoom><img src="/images/hanuman/kneeling.jpg" alt="Hanuman kneeling with folded hands and mace" loading="lazy" /></figure>
        <figure class="tile" data-zoom><img src="/images/hanuman/panchamukhi-slaying.jpg" alt="Pattachitra painting of the fierce protector Hanuman" loading="lazy" /></figure>
        <figure class="tile" data-zoom><img src="/images/hanuman/bhaktha-hanuman.jpg" alt="Hanuman revealing Ram and Sita within his heart" loading="lazy" /></figure>
        <figure class="tile" data-zoom><img src="/images/hanuman/hanuman-mountain.jpg" alt="Hanuman carrying the mountain of healing herbs" loading="lazy" /></figure>
      </div>
      <p class="h-forms-credit">Devotional paintings shared in seva &amp; public-domain works — see <a href="/credits/" class="link-gold">credits →</a></p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Hanuman near Nashik -->
  <section class="shell h-local reveal">
    <div class="h-local-head">
      <span class="eyebrow flanked">Hanuman near Nashik</span>
      <h2>His birthplace, on our doorstep</h2>
      <p>We are blessed — the very hill where Hanuman was born rises just outside Nashik. A handful of beloved Hanuman temples sit close at hand, too. Here is where to find them, and how to reach.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="anjaneri card">
      <div class="anj-text">
        <span class="anj-tag">Hanuman’s birthplace</span>
        <h3>Anjaneri <span class="deva anj-deva">अंजनेरी</span></h3>
        <p>{anjaneri.note}</p>
        <a href={anjaneri.maps} class="link-gold" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Open in Maps →</a>
      </div>
      <dl class="anj-meta">
        <div><dt>Where</dt><dd>{anjaneri.address}</dd></div>
        <div><dt>How to reach</dt><dd>{anjaneri.reach}</dd></div>
      </dl>
    </div>

    <h3 class="h-local-sub">Hanuman temples in the city</h3>
    <div class="temples-grid">
      {localTemples.map((t) => (
        <div class="temple card">
          <h4>{t.name}</h4>
          <span class="temple-area">{t.area}</span>
          <p>{t.note}</p>
          <a href={t.maps} class="link-gold" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Open in Maps →</a>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <p class="h-local-note">Temple timings and trek conditions change with the season — please check locally before you set out, especially during the monsoon. Details gathered from public travel and temple sources; see <a href="/credits/" class="link-gold">credits →</a></p>
  </section>

  <!-- chalisa -->
  <section class="shell-narrow h-chalisa reveal">
    <Divider class="h-rule" />
    <div class="chalisa-card card">
      <span class="eyebrow">Sing along</span>
      <h2 class="deva chalisa-deva">श्री हनुमान चालीसा</h2>
      <p>
        The Hanuman Chalisa — forty verses of praise composed by Tulsidas — is the heartbeat of
        our Tuesday satsang. Whether you know it by heart or are reading along for the first time,
        you are welcome to sing.
      </p>
      <div class="chalisa-actions">
        <a href="/chalisa/" class="btn btn-primary">Sing the Chalisa →</a>
        <a href={CHALISA_PDF} download class="btn btn-ghost">Download (PDF)</a>
      </div>
      <p class="chalisa-jai deva">जय हनुमान ज्ञान गुण सागर</p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .h-hero-img { max-width: 23rem; margin: 1.5rem auto 0.5rem; cursor: zoom-in; }
  .h-hero-img .photo { aspect-ratio: 64 / 88; }
  .h-hero-img figcaption, .h-darbar figcaption { text-align: center; font-style: italic; font-family: var(--font-display); color: var(--color-maroon); font-size: 0.95rem; margin-top: 0.9rem; }
  .h-credit { display: inline-block; font-style: normal; font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: 0.72rem; letter-spacing: 0.08em; color: var(--color-ink-faint); margin-top: 0.2rem; }
  .h-darbar { margin: 2.4rem auto; max-width: 26rem; cursor: zoom-in; }

  .h-body { padding: 1.5rem 0 1rem; }
  .h-lead { font-size: 1.25rem; color: var(--color-ink); font-style: italic; }
  .h-rule { margin-block: 2.6rem; }

  .h-qualities { padding: 2rem 0; }
  .h-qualities .eyebrow { display: flex; justify-content: center; margin-bottom: 1.8rem; }
  .hq-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 1.2rem; }
  .hq-card { padding: 1.8rem; text-align: center; }
  .hq-hi { display: block; font-size: 1.8rem; color: var(--color-saffron); margin-bottom: 0.3rem; }
  .hq-card h3 { font-size: 1.3rem; color: var(--color-maroon); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
  .hq-card p { color: var(--color-ink-soft); font-size: 0.96rem; }
  @media (min-width: 640px) { .hq-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; } }
  @media (min-width: 980px) { .hq-grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr); } }

  /* forms gallery — light */
  .h-forms { margin: 3rem 0 2rem; padding: 2.5rem 0; }
  .h-forms-head { text-align: center; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
  .h-forms-head .eyebrow { display: inline-flex; margin-bottom: 0.8rem; }
  .h-forms-head h2 { font-size: clamp(1.7rem, 4vw, 2.4rem); }
  .h-forms-head p { color: var(--color-ink-soft); max-width: 36rem; margin: 0.6rem auto 0; }
  .h-forms-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); gap: 0.9rem; }
  .h-forms-grid .tile { aspect-ratio: 3 / 4; }
  .h-forms-credit { text-align: center; margin-top: 1.4rem; font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--color-ink-faint); }
  @media (min-width: 760px) { .h-forms-grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); } }

  /* Hanuman near Nashik */
  .h-local { padding: 2.5rem 0 1rem; }
  .h-local-head { text-align: center; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
  .h-local-head .eyebrow { display: inline-flex; margin-bottom: 0.8rem; }
  .h-local-head h2 { font-size: clamp(1.7rem, 4vw, 2.4rem); }
  .h-local-head p { color: var(--color-ink-soft); max-width: 40rem; margin: 0.6rem auto 0; }

  .anjaneri { display: grid; gap: 1.6rem 2.4rem; padding: 2rem; align-items: start;
    background: linear-gradient(160deg, color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-saffron) 9%, var(--color-paper-warm)), var(--color-paper-warm)); }
  .anj-tag { font-family: var(--font-ui); font-size: 0.62rem; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.16em; text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-maroon); background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-maroon) 12%, transparent); padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem; border-radius: 999px; }
  .anjaneri h3 { font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 3.5vw, 2rem); margin: 0.7rem 0 0.5rem; display: flex; align-items: baseline; gap: 0.6rem; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .anj-deva { font-size: 0.7em; color: var(--color-saffron-deep); }
  .anj-text p { color: var(--color-ink-soft); margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .anj-meta { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1.1rem; margin: 0; }
  .anj-meta dt { font-family: var(--font-ui); font-size: 0.68rem; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.14em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--color-maroon); margin-bottom: 0.25rem; }
  .anj-meta dd { margin: 0; color: var(--color-ink-soft); font-size: 0.97rem; line-height: 1.55; }

  .h-local-sub { text-align: center; font-size: 1.3rem; margin: 2.6rem 0 1.3rem; color: var(--color-maroon); }
  .temples-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 1rem; }
  .temple { padding: 1.5rem; display: flex; flex-direction: column; }
  .temple h4 { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1.2rem; margin-bottom: 0.2rem; }
  .temple-area { font-family: var(--font-ui); font-size: 0.74rem; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.05em; color: var(--color-ink-faint); margin-bottom: 0.7rem; }
  .temple p { color: var(--color-ink-soft); font-size: 0.95rem; flex: 1; margin-bottom: 1rem; }

  .h-local-note { text-align: center; font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--color-ink-faint); margin-top: 1.6rem; max-width: 44rem; margin-inline: auto; }

  @media (min-width: 760px) {
    .anjaneri { grid-template-columns: 1.5fr 1fr; }
    .temples-grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); }
  }

  .h-chalisa { padding: 1rem 0 2rem; }
  .chalisa-card { padding: 2.6rem; text-align: center; background: linear-gradient(160deg, color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-saffron) 10%, var(--color-paper-warm)), var(--color-paper-warm)); }
  .chalisa-card .eyebrow { display: inline-flex; margin-bottom: 0.8rem; }
  .chalisa-deva { font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 5vw, 2.6rem); color: var(--color-maroon); margin-bottom: 0.8rem; }
  .chalisa-card p { color: var(--color-ink-soft); max-width: 34rem; margin: 0 auto 1.4rem; }
  .chalisa-actions { display: flex; gap: 0.8rem; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .chalisa-jai { color: var(--color-saffron-deep); margin-top: 1.4rem; font-size: 1.2rem; }
</style>
